- Defaulter: the patient is known by the clinician not to have completed the treatment, and does not come back for assessment

dataElements.name: CL_GEN_EPID_outbreak
dataElements.description:
Please specify if there were any outbreaks of CL reported in your country in the reporting year. 

WHO defines a disease outbreak as the occurrence of cases of disease in excess of what would normally be expected in a defined community, geographical area or season. An outbreak may occur in a restricted geographical area or may extend over several countries. It may last for a few days or weeks, or for several years. 

A single case of a communicable disease long absent from a population, or caused by an agent not previously recognized in that community or area, or the emergence of a previously unknown disease, may also constitute an outbreak and should be reported and investigated.
dataElements.formName: Were there any cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) outbreaks over the reporting year?

dataElements.name: CL_ITxO_Tx-route
dataElements.shortName: CL cases by initial treatment outcome and route
dataElements.description:
The number of confirmed CL cases treated, disaggregated by patient type, treatment route and treatment outcome.

At initial assessment and at the end of the treatment (between 2 and 4 weeks after initiating treatment, depending on drug regimen) these are the treatment outcomes to be recorded:
- Initial cure: a full course of drugs has been completed AND the patient has clinically improved. 
- Failure (non-response): includes both probable failure (signs and symptoms persist or recur during treatment without parasitological confirmation) and confirmed failure (signs and symptoms persist or recur during treatment with parasitological confirmation). 
-Death: any death, whether or not related to CL
-Unknown: the patient has not been assesed by a clinician following treatment, or the result has not been recorded. 

Treatment route options include:  
-Wash/dressing only
-Pentavalent antimonials intralesional only
-Cryotherapy only
-Cryotherapy + pentavalent antimonials                                                                               
-Pentavalent antimonials intramuscular or systemic only 
-Thermotherapy only 
-Other
-Treatment route unknown

Patient type: see CL_EPI_Type for definition

The sum of the number of cases in each category should be equal to the total number of CL cases.
dataElements.formName: Number of CL cases, by initial treatment outcome, treatment route, and patient type

- Unspecified: Please use this category if the type of patient is unknown or not recorded. 

The WHO defines a probable case as a person living in or having travelled to CL-endemic areas showing typical CL skin lesions (macula, plaque, nodule, ulcer) without parasitological confirmation. The case is parasitologically confirmed through positive smear, culture or PCR. 

The sum of the number of cases in each categories should be equal to the total number of CL cases.

dataElements.name: CL_GEN_EPID_new focus
dataElements.description:
Please specify the number of new CL foci reported in your country in this reporting year. 

A focus is a defined and circumscribed geographical implementation unit (region, district, village) containing the epidemiological factors needed for transmission, i.e.:
-a human community
-a source of infection
-a competent vector population, and
-appropriate environmental conditions

In practice for surveillance purposes, a focus is a defined and circumscribed geographical implementation unit where there is evidence that locally acquired confirmed cases have been reported even if the transmission cycle has not been described.
 
A new focus is defined as a focus where leishmaniasis transmission was never reported previously.
dataElements.formName: How many new foci of cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) have been detected in the reporting year?

dataElements.name: CL_Monthly_File
dataElements.description:
Please upload the excel file with the number of confirmed CL cases disaggregated by month and by the smallest administrative level available (ideally administrative level 3). 
Administrative level refers to the probable place of infection. If information is only available on the place of treatment, please indicate this clearly on the first tab of the file. 

Please also indicate if the implementation unit is considered endemic or non-endemic.  
Endemicity of a given area: evidence of ongoing transmission based on ?1 locally acquired confirmed case per year in a defined area, for the previous 10 years.
A country/region/district ceases to be designated endemic when there are 0 locally acquired cases per year in the defined area for the previous 10 years, despite proven surveillance and active case finding.
dataElements.formName: File with number of CL cases by month at subnational level

1. EPIDEMIOLOGY

Case definitions

Probable CL case: WHO defines a probable case of cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) as a person living in or having travelled to CL-endemic areas showing typical CL skin lesions (macula, plaque, nodule, ulcer).

Confirmed CL case

  • Lab-Confirmed CL case: WHO defines a lab-confirmed case of cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) as a probable case of CL with parasitological confirmation of the diagnosis (positive smear or culture or PCR).
  • OR Clinically-Confirmed CL case: WHO defines a clinically-confirmed case of cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) as a probable CL case which has not been confirmed by laboratory (test not done or negative), but the clinician decides on clinical grounds that the case is clinically confirmed.

1.1 Confirmed CL Cases (either laboratory or clinically), by Type

Relapse: WHO defines a relapse as a CL case who experiences recurrence of typical CL lesions with parasitological confirmation at any time point after cure.

6. FINAL TREATMENT OUTCOME

At final assessment (6 months after the last drug has been taken), WHO defines as:
• Final cure: an initially cured patient who is symptom-free at six months after the end of treatment.
• Relapse: any reappearance of CL symptoms within a period of six months after the end of treatment.
• Death: any death, whether or not related to CL.
